messages.message: Uploaded patch set 1.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2 Sanity-Review+1

Apparently pushing a Work In Progress

Patch Set 1:

First of all, I think the linked bug is significantly more serious than the bug which was fixed in the linked commit (assigning a constant value to when is probably not that common as a use case); so if we do not use this fix, we  should probably revert it.

Now, as is evident by the unit test change, this fix has the potential to break other code, as querying an Item's state will now give you an outdated result unless you wait for one event loop iteration. On the plus side, both the old and the new bug are fixed, and for decoratively written QML, there shouldn't be an observable change.

@Thomas: Design Studio makes heavy use of States, doesn't it? From that perspective, what's your opinion on the fix? I assume you've not upgraded to Qt > 5.14 yet, else you most likely would have encountered the linked bug.

Patch Set 1:

In a typical example using e.g. "when: mouseArea.containsMouse" the effect is not visible (But the issue is triggered).
Seems like the item is in the wrong state not even for one frame.

Patch Set 1:

> Now, as is evident by the unit test change, this fix has the potential to break other code, as querying an Item's state will now give you an outdated result unless you wait for one event loop iteration.

This was my main concern as well after looking through the change. In my opinion properties with asynchronous effects often come with gotchas:
 * it is why we need methods like Row::forceLayout
 * it makes StateMachine::running a pain to use (see comments of QTBUG-55023, as well as QTBUG-55024)
 * it is why Qt Remote Objects made READPUSH the default for its properties

> First of all, I think the linked bug is significantly more serious than the bug which was fixed in the linked commit (assigning a constant value to when is probably not that common as a use case); so if we do not use this fix, we  should probably revert it.

Agree on the relative severities, and I'd probably vote to revert (particularly for Qt 5.x).

Thanks for the detailed notes.

Patch Set 1:

> Agree on the relative severities, and I'd probably vote to revert (particularly for Qt 5.x).

Strongly agree with reverting 64c1fbe96c68b1286a70242ff4922be140128cb2. This bug makes it very difficult for many code bases to upgrade through the 5.12 > 5.15 > 6.2 LTS upgrade path whereas QTBUG-76838 is easy to live with (less common, easier to detect, easier to workaround). Meanwhile, the longer QTBUG-86695 exists, the more code will be written that might depend on this buggy behavior.
